==============================================================
  SECURITY FINDING NOTIFICATION  |  F-03  |  HIGH
==============================================================

Finding ID    : F-03
Severity      : HIGH
OWASP Ref     : API3:2023 — Broken Object Property Level Authorization
API Tested    : JSONPlaceholder (https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com)
Endpoint      : GET /users/1
Date Discovered: Mon, 27 Apr 2026
Analyst       : CrazyCoder

--------------------------------------------------------------
DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------

The single-user endpoint returns significantly more data fields than any
typical API consumer requires. While a mobile app displaying a user profile
needs only the user's name and email, the response additionally includes
geo-coordinates, full physical address, personal website URL, and internal
company metadata. This violates the principle of data minimization.

--------------------------------------------------------------
PROOF OF CONCEPT  (Evidence)
--------------------------------------------------------------

REQUEST:
  GET https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/1
  Response: 200 OK

FULL RESPONSE BODY (annotated):
  {
    "id": 1,                                  -- needed (user identity)
    "name": "Leanne Graham",                  -- needed (display name)
    "username": "Bret",                       -- needed (login identifier)
    "email": "Sincere@april.biz",             -- needed (contact)
    "address": {
      "street": "Kulas Light",                -- OVER-EXPOSED: physical address
      "suite": "Apt. 556",                    -- OVER-EXPOSED: physical address
      "city": "Gwenborough",                  -- OVER-EXPOSED: physical address
      "zipcode": "92998-3874",                -- OVER-EXPOSED: physical address
      "geo": {
        "lat": "-37.3159",                    -- OVER-EXPOSED: precise GPS lat
        "lng": "81.1496"                      -- OVER-EXPOSED: precise GPS lng
      }
    },
    "phone": "1-770-736-8031 x56442",         -- OVER-EXPOSED: personal phone
    "website": "hildegard.org",               -- OVER-EXPOSED: personal website
    "company": {
      "name": "Romaguera-Crowe",              -- situational need
      "catchPhrase": "Multi-layered neural-net", -- OVER-EXPOSED: internal meta
      "bs": "harness real-time e-markets"     -- OVER-EXPOSED: internal meta
    }
  }

OVER-EXPOSED FIELDS IDENTIFIED: 7 (geo.lat, geo.lng, address fields x4,
company.catchPhrase, company.bs, website)

--------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS IMPACT
--------------------------------------------------------------

1. Precise geo-coordinates (lat/lng) can reveal a user's home or workplace
   location — a direct personal safety risk for domestic abuse survivors,
   whistleblowers, and anyone avoiding a hostile party.

2. Over-exposed fields multiply the damage of any other vulnerability.
   Combined with F-01 (unauthenticated access), all geo-coordinates for all
   users are publicly available to anyone on the internet.

3. Internal metadata fields (catchPhrase, bs) may reveal system architecture
   or business categorization logic useful to attackers planning targeted
   social engineering attacks.

4. Returning PII fields with no stated consumer purpose may constitute a
   violation of India's DPDP Act 2023 data minimization requirements.

--------------------------------------------------------------
REMEDIATION  (Priority: SHORT-TERM — fix within current sprint)
--------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1: Define a separate UserProfileResponse DTO (Data Transfer Object)
        for the /users/{id} endpoint. Include only the fields that a
        documented consumer use case requires:
        class UserProfileResponse(BaseModel):
            id: int
            name: str
            username: str
            email: str

Step 2: Never return raw database model objects from API endpoints.
        Always map to a scoped response schema before returning.

Step 3: Conduct a field-level audit of every response schema.
        For each field, document: "which client use case requires this?"
        Remove all fields with no active use case.

Step 4: Add API response schema linting to your CI/CD pipeline.
        Fail the build if a response includes fields in a deny-list
        (e.g. geo, internal metadata keys like "bs", "catchPhrase").

